= content_for(:page_title) do
  Docker

- # The example config files: filename and purpose, rendered as a table.
- config_files = []
- config_files << ["docker-compose.yml", "Defines your application services"]
- config_files << ["Dockerfile", "Instructions for building your app container"]
- config_files << ["dev/Dockerfile", "Development environment container"]
- config_files << ["entrypoint.sh", "Script that runs when containers start"]
- config_files << ["justfile", "Shortcuts for common commands"]

.max-w-prose
  = doc_info(url: "https://www.docker.com/", image_path: "logos/docker.svg", image_alt: "Docker Logo") do
    :markdown
      _Loco_**Motion** recommends using Docker for a consistent and reliable
      development environment!

.prose
  :markdown
    # Docker Development Environment

    We recommend using Docker to get your project setup from the beginning. This
    ensures that you have a stable development environment, no matter what OS or
    system you're using to develop.

    It also allows you to troubleshoot and debug the application since the
    development container is small and simple with very few dependencies.

- # The roadmap: three setup steps plus the hand-off to Rails Setup.
- # The links opt out of Turbo because the layout wraps pages in a
- # turbo-frame, which would otherwise swallow same-page anchor jumps.
.mt-8.rounded-box.border.border-base-300.p-6
  = daisy_steps(css: "w-full steps-vertical sm:steps-horizontal") do |steps|
    - steps.with_step(css: "step-primary") do
      %a{ href: "#setup", class: "link-hover", data: { turbo: "false" } } Install the tools
    - steps.with_step(css: "step-primary") do
      %a{ href: "#config", class: "link-hover", data: { turbo: "false" } } Copy the config
    - steps.with_step(css: "step-primary") do
      %a{ href: "#start", class: "link-hover", data: { turbo: "false" } } Start it up
    - steps.with_step do
      %a{ href: "#next", class: "link-hover", data: { turbo: "false" } } Create your app 🎉

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "setup", class: "scroll-mt-24" } 1. Initial Setup
  :markdown
    First, you'll need to install Docker. You can download it from
    [Docker's website](https://www.docker.com/).

    You'll also need [Just](https://github.com/casey/just), the command
    runner we use for every shortcut in the `justfile`. Install it with your
    package manager — for example `brew install just` on macOS — or follow
    the
    [installation instructions](https://github.com/casey/just#installation)
    for other platforms.

    Once both are installed, create a new directory for your project:

.max-w-prose
  = daisy_code(css: "my-4") do |code|
    - code.with_line(prefix: "$") do
      mkdir -p ~/Development/mycompany/myproject
    - code.with_line(prefix: "$") do
      cd ~/Development/mycompany/myproject

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "config", class: "scroll-mt-24" } 2. Configuration Files
  :markdown
    Look in the `examples` directory of the [LocoMotion
    repository](https://github.com/profoundry-us/loco_motion/tree/main/examples)
    for these basic configuration files:

- # The config files as a table (dogfooding daisy_table) instead of a
- # bullet list.
.mt-4.max-w-2xl.overflow-x-auto.rounded-box.border.border-base-300
  = daisy_table(css: "table-zebra") do |table|
    - table.with_head do |head|
      - head.with_column { "File" }
      - head.with_column { "Purpose" }
    - config_files.each do |file, purpose|
      - table.with_row do |row|
        - row.with_column do
          %code= file
        - row.with_column do
          = purpose

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Copy these files into your project directory. Your directory structure should
    look like this:

  = doc_code(language: "text") do
    :plain
      ~/Development
      └── mycompany
          └── myproject
              ├── Dockerfile
              ├── justfile
              ├── dev
              │   └── Dockerfile
              ├── docker-compose.yml
              └── entrypoint.sh

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "start", class: "scroll-mt-24" } 3. Starting the Development Environment
  :markdown
    With these files in place, you can now start your development environment:

.max-w-prose
  = daisy_code(css: "my-4", prefix: "$") do
    just dev

.prose
  :markdown
    This command will build and run all the necessary containers. Once they have
    started, open a shell in your development container with:

.max-w-prose
  = daisy_code(css: "my-4", prefix: "$") do
    just dev-shell

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "next", class: "scroll-mt-24" } Next: Create Your App
  :markdown
    With the containers built and a shell open via `just dev-shell`, your
    development environment is ready — consistent across any OS, simple to
    debug, and isolated from your host system's dependencies.

    From here, the [Rails Setup guide](#{guide_path("rails_setup")}) picks up
    exactly where this one leaves off: creating the Rails app with
    `rails new`, configuring the database, and applying the
    LocoMotion-recommended setup (UUIDs, HAML, DaisyUI, and more).

= daisy_button "Continue to Rails Setup", css: "btn-secondary btn-soft btn-sm mt-4", right_icon: "arrow-right", href: guide_path("rails_setup"), turbo_frame: "_top", turbo_action: "advance", action: "click->nav#refresh"

= daisy_divider

= doc_buttons(css: "mt-8", current_id: params[:id])
